A few tips to make filled pasta:
・Both the dough and the filling can be made in advance.
・A spray bottle of water is invaluable! A light misting will keep the hydrated without making it too wet. It also makes shaping, filling, and sealing filled pastas easier.
・Overstuffing filled pastas makes shaping and sealing challenging and may result in bursting during cooking. 
・I often use a small round cookie cutter that fits snugly just around the filling to shape the filling and help push out the air that may be trapped.

Hope that helps! Happy pasta making!

Special bonus recipe. Bookmark it to bake this weekend. My DEAD EASY Coconut Cake. Make it on Sunday and have it to snack on for the week. Yes, it stays moist for that long. And if it's last till Friday, you can pan fry it in butter, and add a scoop of ice cream for dessert. This is my stepmother’s, Jenny's recipe that she's been making forever. It's foolproof and fabulous. Give it a spin.

Makes 
8x 2-inch round pan. Bake 30-35 mins
9 x 5 loaf pan. Bake 50 mins.
12 cupcakes. bake 17-20 mins.

Ingredients:
1 cup (130g) all-purpose flour
1 teaspoon baking powder
1⁄4 teaspoon salt
1 cup (70g) fine dried shredded unsweetened coconut
3⁄4 cup (150g) granulated sugar
2 eggs, at room temperature
2⁄3 cup (160ml) well-stirred unsweetened coconut milk (or whole milk)
8 tablespoons (1 stick/115g) unsalted butter, melted

1.Preheat the oven to 350°F. Grease and line pan.
2.In a mixing bowl, add the flour, baking powder, salt, coconut and sugar and combine. 
3.In a small bowl, whisk together the eggs and coconut milk. Add the wet ingredients to the dry ingredients and combined. Finally, add the melted butter and stir until smooth.
4.Pour the batter into the prepared pan. Bake in the center of the oven until a wooden skewer inserted in the center comes out clean, and the cake bounces back when lightly pressed.
5.Remove the cake from the oven, cool on a wire rack.

I can assure you that this is going to be the best flan you’ve made yet. Remember to go low and slow, and don’t use a whisk to combine the handful of ingredients, as we don’t want any air bubbles blemishing the creamy complexion. 

But equally as important, do not, under any circumstances, serve it with fruit, or worse, a mint leaf. It doesn’t need it. Show some restraint and let the beautiful, cascading caramel and a dollop of condensed-milk whipped cream do the work. 

Head over to my #partytrick column at @wsjoffduty for the complete recipe now. ⁠
⁠
⁠
Condensed-Milk Whipped Cream:⁠
⁠
1 cup heavy cream, chilled⁠
¼ cup condensed milk⁠
⁠
In a cold, preferably metal mixing bowl, whisk together cream and condensed milk, until soft peaks form. To serve, slice flan and dollop on condensed-milk whipped cream. That’s it.⁠

Let’s start the week the right way. As promised, here’s the recipe for my Super-Dirty Preserved Lemon Martini from #simplepasta. Cheers! 🍸🍋⁠
⁠
Ingredients:⁠
⁠
2 ounces gin⁠
1 ounce dry vermouth⁠
2 teaspoons green olive brine, plus 3 green olives⁠
2 teaspoons preserved lemon brine or lemon juice, plus preserved lemon rind for garnishing⁠
⁠
1. Place a martini glass in the freezer to chill for 5 minutes.⁠
2. Pour the gin, vermouth, olive brine, and preserved lemon brine into a cocktail shaker or tall mixing glass filled with ice. Shake or stir until very well chilled, then strain into the prepared glass.⁠
3. Garnish with a toothpick threaded with the olives and a sliver of preserved lemon rind and serve.⁠
⁠

My ride or die. Carbonara.⁠
⁠
I’ve had a long and complicated relationship with⁠
carbonara. I’ve committed all sorts of crimes against it.⁠
When I was thirteen, I made a version using béchamel⁠
sauce; way too thick and stodgy. By my late teens, I had⁠
graduated to using heavy cream—a lighter affair than⁠
the béchamel—an improvement but not an egg in sight.⁠
And I still hadn’t worked out the correct ratio of pasta to⁠
sauce. Eventually, I learned how to emulsify eggs, pork⁠
fat, cheese, and pasta water to create a creamy coating⁠
on the sturdy pasta. But here’s my truth, and it might⁠
be controversial: Sometimes I find carbonara too eggy.⁠
My version doesn’t go crazy on the eggs, and hopefully⁠
alleviates any fear of scrambling them. To compensate,⁠
I add a little more oil and infuse it with garlic. Okay,⁠
okay . . . even now, I’m not doing the “right” thing by this⁠
Roman classic, but at the end of the day, everyone finds⁠
their own carbonara.⁠ Foolproof recipe is in Simple Pasta. 🍝

@la_tonnarella I made it. Can cross this off the bucket list, and put it on the must return one. It’s a dream. Arriving by boat, tomatoes ripening hanging in clusters, eating salty shrimp, whole fish cooked simply, crab pasta with roe in the shell, and washing it all down with white wine with peaches. I have very strong feelings about fruit bobbing in alcohol, and they aren’t positive. But this carafe made me reconsider. The stone fruit was really firm, sliced thinly, and everything was served icy, so it worked. I’m having a party in a couple of weeks and I’ll be definitely doing this. You just need a really easy, Italian white, that’s so effortless you can drink it like water. You know the kind right? 

Summer, you’ve been ace.

“Is it heaven? It’s heaven, isn’t it? You’re in heaven.” This was the text I got from a friend when he saw I was traveling on the Amalfi Coast of Italy recently. “Soak it up. I just saw Chick-fil-A delivered to your door…so kids are good!” 

If you’re not one of the millions expected to visit Italy this summer, this recipe will get you there in spirit. I wouldn’t normally think to make a risotto in summer, but Amalfi restaurants @ristoranteloscoglio and @la_tonnarella showed me what a spectacular choice it is for an easy-breezy al fresco lunch or dinner. Imagine you’ve arrived by boat, salty, sun-kissed, ravenous from swimming.

It’s about this time of year, around this time of night, when I start to crave either custard, or rice pudding. Words cannot express how deeply I love these two desserts. Pure comfort. This is not a thick stodgy rice pudding, rather one that takes it cues from a silky Kheer. I love it served hot or cold. Whatever temp you choose, hit the save tab, as you will be making this all winter long. Share with a friend, and make sure to leave yourself a cheeky bowl for the morning to have with your coffee. I love you. You’re welcome. 

VANILLA BEAN RICE PUDDING

Ingredients

¾ cup basmati rice 
10 cups whole milk
1 vanilla bean, seeds and pod 
¾ cup granulated sugar
⅓ cup unsalted hazelnuts, toasted, rubbed skins and roughly chopped 

Directions

In a small bowl, add the sugar and use your fingers to work the vanilla bean seeds into the sugar. Set aside.

In a large heavy-based pot, add the rice, milk and vanilla bean pod. Bring to a gentle boil over medium heat. Lower the heat and simmer, stirring very often with a wooden spoon, for about an hour. Make sure you don’t scrape the bottom of the pot as you might discolor your pudding. 

Remove the pot from the heat and discard the vanilla bean.

Add the vanilla bean sugar and fold in half of the nuts. 

To serve, divide the rice pudding into bowls, and sprinkle the remaining hazelnuts.
